    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Leon<lb/>
                I venture to send this letter to the<lb/> Post Office&#44; not knowing your direction.  If it<lb/> comes to hand&#44; you will hear my determination.<lb/>  I leave you to your fate.  You have chosen<lb/> to grieve me deeply&#44; and perhaps bring<lb/> disgrace upon my name&#59; I must do violence<lb/> to my feelings and let you suffer among<lb/> strangers.  You know too well my efforts<lb/> in trying to secure for you a respectable situa&#45;<lb/>&#45;tion&#44; by which you might hereafter earn a<lb/> decent livelihood.  After much worriment&#44;<lb/> you obtained it&#44; and because you could not<lb/> immediately earn a few dollars&#44; which you<lb/> do not need&#44; you abandoned a comfortable<lb/> home&#44; and cared nothing about the sorrow that<lb/> your step would bring to your indulgent father<lb/> and affectionate sisters.  Well&#58; follow your<lb/> own option&#44; only do not cause me to suffer<lb/> the severest blow&#45;&#45;the loss of my good name.<lb/>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
                I have not written to the children on this<lb/> unfortunate occurrence&#44; for I don&#39;t want to mar<lb/> their pleasure&#44; and bring them home before the<lb/> time&#44; but I was compelled to tell it to Mr<lb/> Levy.  He had just returned from Baltimore&#44;<lb/> and he was told that you were sick.  He intended<lb/> coming to our house to inquire&#44; when I called<lb/> and said to him that you had gone.  He never<lb/> would have imagined that a boy situated as you<lb/> are would commit such a sad fault&#44; but he spoke<lb/> kindly of you&#44; and regretted that you cannot<lb/> understand your own interest.<lb/>
                I suppose that in order to go to the New York&#44; you<lb/> pawned&#44; possibly you sold&#44; your watch&#44; which was<lb/> given you as a memento on a solemn occasion just<lb/> a year ago.  May God forgive you all<lb/> the misdeeds you committed&#44; and the trouble<lb/> you have given<lb/> Your father<lb/> 
                Philadelphia August 1st 1883<lb/></p>
        </body>
